WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:03.420
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:03.420 --> 00:00:08.250
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Really, it
is an honor to talk to you.

00:00:08.250 --> 00:00:09.550
It's wonderful.

00:00:09.550 --> 00:00:10.850
I'm glad we could do this.

00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:12.150
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Thank you.

00:00:12.150 --> 00:00:13.450
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Let me try to
set the story a little bit.

00:00:13.450 --> 00:00:16.660
Javier Mallarino, your protagonist,

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:20.330
is the best-known political
cartoonist

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:24.360
in a political environment
that can be lethal.

00:00:24.360 --> 00:00:25.660
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Yes.

00:00:25.660 --> 00:00:28.530 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I think it's fair to
say, Columbia of a generation ago.

00:00:28.530 --> 00:00:33.030
Describe that territory
to us, if you could.

00:00:33.030 --> 00:00:34.340
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: First
of all, I'd like to thank you

00:00:34.340 --> 00:00:39.140
and thank you all for coming, to
thank Mr. Ambassador for his words.

00:00:39.140 --> 00:00:42.360
I always have the impression that
ambassadors are always trying

00:00:42.360 --> 00:00:47.620
to redress what we
novelists mess up.

00:00:47.620 --> 00:00:48.920
[Laughter].

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:52.980
To thank you very much.

00:00:52.980 --> 00:01:05.530
Yeah, this novel was written in
2012-2013 at a point in which I had

00:01:05.530 --> 00:01:10.790
to explain to readers
outside of my country the fact

00:01:10.790 --> 00:01:15.200 position:56%
that this story the novel tells us
is actually plausible in my country.

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:17.590
It is the story of
a cartoonist who is

00:01:17.590 --> 00:01:21.620
so powerful that he is threatened.

00:01:21.620 --> 00:01:24.570
He is feared.

00:01:24.570 --> 00:01:28.620
He is very well respected.

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:33.230
He is able to change the climate

00:01:33.230 --> 00:01:36.690
of political opinion
in very direct ways.

00:01:36.690 --> 00:01:40.370
In 2013, this was not
easily understandable

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:42.540
in countries other than mine.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:46.760 position:56%
We have a strong tradition of
cartoonists who are actually this --

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:50.130
very powerful people whose
opinions are respected.

00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:58.080
Coming from the 19th century, and
in particular, a cartoonist working

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:08.560
in the 20s who was a tremendous
symbol of what the relationship

00:02:08.560 --> 00:02:14.800
between political opinion and the
political world was in my country.

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:18.740
His name was Ricardo
Rendon [phonetic].

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:23.400
This is the character but
also tries to put in place.

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:30.930 position:56%
This person who, through drying
politicians in a national newspaper,

00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:35.060
is able to achieve real
political influence

00:02:35.060 --> 00:02:43.600
and to model the political
discussion in my country.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:49.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Even the
politicians whom he savages are kind

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:51.610
of flattered by it,
because it means they count.

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:53.880
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
Well, they exist, yes.

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:57.040
They have figured out
that being destroyed

00:02:57.040 --> 00:03:02.350
by Javier Mallarino is
effectively to exist

00:03:02.350 --> 00:03:05.330
in the political world in Columbia.

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:12.830
But the thing is, that
kind of power in the hands

00:03:12.830 --> 00:03:17.750
of a political cartoonist is
not something that my readers

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:21.090
in translation were
used to five years ago.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:23.700
And this has been a
very interesting,

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:26.840
a very dramatic thing
for me to witness.

00:03:26.840 --> 00:03:33.040
Within four years, since the novel
was published in 2013 in Spanish,

00:03:33.040 --> 00:03:38.620
the world has changed so much, that
actually is more understandable

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:47.550 position:56%
that political cartoonists are
influential, because they have been.

00:03:47.550 --> 00:03:54.470
In terms of international news,
everybody knows what has happened

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:58.100
with political cartoonists
such as those

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:03.000
in the Charlie Hebdo
magazine in France.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.820
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I know you spent
some years living in Paris,

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:11.580
but you wrote this novel
before Charlie Hebdo.

00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:13.260
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Yes.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:15.970
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Before
the terrible crime.

00:04:15.970 --> 00:04:17.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Yeah, yeah.

00:04:17.270 --> 00:04:20.550
Before that horrible thing.

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:26.460
That happened, I think,
maybe a couple of years

00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:29.450
after my novel was published.

00:04:29.450 --> 00:04:33.120
It was a couple of years later

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:35.420
because the French translation
had already appeared.

00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:40.930
So yeah, it had this weird
coincidence in time for me.

00:04:40.930 --> 00:04:43.820
The fact that the novel
was becoming reality

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:45.790
in so many countries in the world.

00:04:45.790 --> 00:04:48.890
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: As the story
opens, the cartoonist is

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:53.260
about to be given the honor of
having his self caricature put

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:55.200
on a national postage stamp.

00:04:55.200 --> 00:05:01.320
He comes in contact with a young
woman who he doesn't remember.

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:06.210
She's posing as a reporter, which
by the way, is astonishingly easy.

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:13.800
Takes no knowledge whatsoever --
I'm in some position to tell you.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:16.580
Let me put it this way, he
comes to terms with the fact

00:05:16.580 --> 00:05:20.670
that what he does, does not
always have positive consequences.

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:21.970 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: That's more

00:05:21.970 --> 00:05:23.300
of the situation explored
in the novel.

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:27.420
Yes. This young lady, we're
not going to reveal too much

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:32.040
of the plot -- don't worry.

00:05:32.040 --> 00:05:38.250
Petition lady comes to him
to ask him to remember,

00:05:38.250 --> 00:05:45.310
to remember the past, to remember a
night that happened 28 years before

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:53.650
in which something may or may not
have happened at Mallarino's house.

00:05:53.650 --> 00:06:04.120
That event, of that night,
caused Mallarino to draw one

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:09.710
of his most famous cartoons.

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:14.050
And this girl, who 28 years
later, she is asking him

00:06:14.050 --> 00:06:17.130
to remember what he
saw during that night.

00:06:17.130 --> 00:06:23.480
And he realizes that he may not
have seen what he thinks he saw.

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:30.150
That his cartoon, after
all, may be groundless.

00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:34.570
This is the situation
explored in the novel.

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:40.840
It was very strange for me to begin
a novel in which my main subject,

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:49.120
my main idea, was the discussion
of the vulnerability of our image

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:53.360
in the hands of people who have
an influence on public opinion.

00:06:53.360 --> 00:06:58.060
But as the novel progressed,
I realized I was writing

00:06:58.060 --> 00:07:01.160
about something else also.

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:03.500
I was writing about
the vulnerability

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:05.800
of our private memories, the fact

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:08.260
that we are never sure
of what we remember.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:12.600
This difficult relationship
we have with memory became one

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:16.230
of the main themes in the novel.

00:07:16.230 --> 00:07:17.690
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: There are
lots I could read from.

00:07:17.690 --> 00:07:21.910
It's beautifully written
and beautifully translated.

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:23.910 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Beautifully
translated by Ann McLean.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.230
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I have to ask,
why didn't you do the translation?

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:31.820
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Because
Ann McLean would be out of a job.

00:07:31.820 --> 00:07:33.930
[Laughter].

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:36.070
She is a friend of mine.

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:38.110
I don't want to do that.

00:07:38.110 --> 00:07:41.530
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: You have
done some translation.

00:07:41.530 --> 00:07:45.590
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
No, the real reason is

00:07:45.590 --> 00:07:55.890
that literature is too difficult
to -- Let's put it this way,

00:07:55.890 --> 00:07:58.260
you should always have
done some translation.

00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:01.160
I've earned a living
as a translator.

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:03.970
But you translate towards
your own language,

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:09.180
because this is the language
in which you are close to 100%.

00:08:09.180 --> 00:08:15.580 position:56%
I'm not close to 100% in English and
that's something I prefer to leave

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:17.430
in the hands of somebody who is.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:26.260
And I have this great luck of
having one of the best translators

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:29.090
of Spanish-language
literature in the world.

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:36.390
That doesn't mean I don't
dig in as soon as I can.

00:08:36.390 --> 00:08:38.680
We work closely together.

00:08:38.680 --> 00:08:44.210
I try to bother her
as much as I can.

00:08:44.210 --> 00:08:48.500
But I never lose sight of the
fact that for me as a translator,

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:50.680
one of the worst things
in the world was a writer

00:08:50.680 --> 00:08:54.170
who thought they knew my language.

00:08:54.170 --> 00:08:57.710
So I try never to be that
writer -- so Ann McLean.

00:08:57.710 --> 00:09:03.240
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I want to read
a section and ask you about it.

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:04.850
I love this section.

00:09:04.850 --> 00:09:07.580
"Life is the best caricature.

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:11.370
Life turns us into
caricatures of ourselves.

00:09:11.370 --> 00:09:14.700
We all have the obligation to
make the best caricature possible,

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:20.230
to camouflage what we don't like,
and exalt what we like best.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:22.720
You will understand, says the
cartoonist, I'm just not talking

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:27.380
about physical attributes, but the
mysterious life traces life leads

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:31.140
on our features, the moral
landscape, if you will.

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:35.030 position:56%
That moral landscape that gets
drawn onto our face as life goes by,

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:40.530
as we go along making mistakes
or getting things right."

00:09:40.530 --> 00:09:47.300
It reminded me, there's a
story of Abraham Lincoln,

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:50.100
who used to be a model for
presidential disposition,

00:09:50.100 --> 00:09:51.950
but of course has recently
been replaced.

00:09:51.950 --> 00:09:56.210
I'm sorry, I just have to
avoid these cheap jokes.

00:09:56.210 --> 00:10:01.510
But Lincoln notably was resisting
the urging of some of his aides

00:10:01.510 --> 00:10:04.440
to appoint someone as the
local postmaster somewhere.

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:05.990
And they said why,
and he said, "Well,

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:07.290
because I don't like his face."

00:10:07.290 --> 00:10:10.170
And they said, "Mr. President,
you can't refuse to appoint a man

00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:11.470
because you don't like his face."

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:14.080
And he said, "Nonsense,
after the age of 40,

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:16.610
every man is responsible
for his own face."

00:10:16.610 --> 00:10:17.910
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Very good.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:19.210
Very good.

00:10:19.210 --> 00:10:23.160
I wish you had told me that before.

00:10:23.160 --> 00:10:24.460
[Cross-talk].

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:28.610
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: But help
us understand a caricature

00:10:28.610 --> 00:10:31.980
at how the cartoonist sees his art.

00:10:31.980 --> 00:10:38.080
Because that has something to do
with literature too, doesn't it?

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:39.380
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
Yes in a way.

00:10:39.380 --> 00:10:45.650
For me to have something to do
with journalism and the terms

00:10:45.650 --> 00:10:49.300
that I understood journalism at the
time when I was writing the book.

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:53.810
I used to be a weekly political
columnist in my country.

00:10:53.810 --> 00:10:55.520
I did that for seven years.

00:10:55.520 --> 00:11:00.010
I wrote political columns
weekly for seven years.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:06.600 position:56%
Then I stopped because I was writing
a very long, very difficult novel

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:13.990
that I will inflict
on you all next year.

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:18.210
To have both things at the
same time, it became difficult.

00:11:18.210 --> 00:11:20.710
So I quit political
commentary for a while.

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:23.990
I still do it once in a while,
every time something pops

00:11:23.990 --> 00:11:31.340 position:56%
up that makes me angry or indignant,
which is most of the time.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:39.970
But this idea of -- this particular
relationship we have as columnists

00:11:39.970 --> 00:11:48.480
with readers, these
distortions of relationships

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:54.290
that I began witnessing the way
it's very easy to create tensions

00:11:54.290 --> 00:11:56.880
in a room just by walking in.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:03.090
The way I lost friends, the
way I had fights with family.

00:12:03.090 --> 00:12:07.580
All my neurosis went into the
character of Javier Mallarino.

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:13.520
So discussing Colombian
political reality

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:19.360
in print was what led directly
to the character and the way

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:23.230
and the position he has, or
rather the relationship he has

00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:28.930
with his readers in Columbia.

00:12:28.930 --> 00:12:31.120
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Is that what
we do with our memories?

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:34.350
Do we caricature our
life experience?

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:39.240
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: I
think we streamline them, yes.

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:43.670
I mean, nobody knows
really how memory works.

00:12:43.670 --> 00:12:50.070
This is one of the ideas
at the center of the book.

00:12:50.070 --> 00:12:57.670
This immense talent memory has
to manipulate us the way --

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:03.570
our memories are obviously
the only window we have

00:13:03.570 --> 00:13:06.530
into our past experiences.

00:13:06.530 --> 00:13:08.680
There's nothing else.

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:11.670
Obviously, there are
other people's memories,

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:15.010
and this is why we read books.

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:21.430
But this window so fragile,
so easily distorted,

00:13:21.430 --> 00:13:26.100
so tainted by subjectivity,
by prejudice,

00:13:26.100 --> 00:13:30.560
by whatever we would
have liked to happen.

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:33.480
This is more or less
what we remember.

00:13:33.480 --> 00:13:36.700
Or rather, we are very,
very good at suppressing.

00:13:36.700 --> 00:13:39.510
Obviously, this is commonplace.

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:44.740
We are very good at
suppressing what we don't like.

00:13:44.740 --> 00:13:51.660
So this relationship with memory
became very interesting for me.

00:13:51.660 --> 00:13:53.290
How it manipulates us.

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:56.370
How we are never sure
really that we experienced

00:13:56.370 --> 00:13:59.740
or witnessed what we think
we witnessed or experienced.

00:13:59.740 --> 00:14:03.310
And this is what happens
to the character,

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:06.500
who thinks he sees something

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:12.650
and then draws a very
controversial cartoon

00:14:12.650 --> 00:14:16.460
which has a strong impact
on somebody else's life.

00:14:16.460 --> 00:14:21.080
And so, years later he doesn't
really know what was there.

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:24.130
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I think a lot of
Americans who read about the life

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:28.040
of Richard Nixon might be
reminded it's sometimes hard

00:14:28.040 --> 00:14:34.460
to enlist a sympathetic memory for
Richard Nixon for many Americans.

00:14:34.460 --> 00:14:38.320
But there was perhaps the great
political cartoonist of his time,

00:14:38.320 --> 00:14:46.400
Herb Block of Washington Post,
did a very noteworthy caricature,

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:50.060
day after day obviously in the
news of this very swarthy, bearded,

00:14:50.060 --> 00:14:53.890
sort of 5 o'clock shadow Nixon.

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:59.100
And he told interviewer
a number of years ago

00:14:59.100 --> 00:15:03.250 position:56%
that he would bring the Post in
when it was delivered in the morning

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:06.080
so his daughters wouldn't see it,

00:15:06.080 --> 00:15:08.650
because he didn't want
his daughters --

00:15:08.650 --> 00:15:09.950
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Yes.

00:15:09.950 --> 00:15:11.860
I got the story, or
variations of that story,

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:15.790
quite often while I was
researching for the novel.

00:15:15.790 --> 00:15:20.810
Perhaps the greatest
cartoonist of his generation

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:24.500
in Columbia is called
Vlado [phonetic].

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:27.980
His pen name is Vlado.

00:15:27.980 --> 00:15:31.150
He has become a friend of mine
since the writing of the novel

00:15:31.150 --> 00:15:34.330
because he was a source
of information for me,

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:37.010 position:56%
an invaluable source of information.

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:39.660
And one of the stories
he told me was

00:15:39.660 --> 00:15:44.650
that once he had started
making cartoons

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:52.390
of this very powerful military
man in Columbia, who at the time,

00:15:52.390 --> 00:15:59.350
used these dark glasses,
sort of Pinochet style.

00:15:59.350 --> 00:16:07.550
And he had very crooked teeth,
extremely crooked smile.

00:16:07.550 --> 00:16:10.910
And this is the way he was drawn.

00:16:10.910 --> 00:16:16.570 position:56%
So one day my friend the
cartoonist gets this message from --

00:16:16.570 --> 00:16:23.190
I think he was a general --
asking him for a meeting.

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:26.500
So when the general
asks the cartoonist

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.020
for a meeting, you understand --

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:31.560
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Did he drive
a tank up to his office?

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:33.560
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: I
think there was nowhere to park.

00:16:33.560 --> 00:16:43.500
In the meeting he said, "Look,
I have change my glasses.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:48.630
I have gone to the dentist.

00:16:48.630 --> 00:16:52.070
And you still draw
me as I was before.

00:16:52.070 --> 00:16:53.370
Please don't do that.

00:16:53.370 --> 00:16:55.700
My children hate the drawings.

00:16:55.700 --> 00:16:57.000
They make fun of me.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.010
My wife is sad, etc, etc."

00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:03.000
My friend said, "General,
that money is down the drain,

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.810
because I will join you as I wish.

00:17:05.810 --> 00:17:11.790 position:56%
This is your cartoon persona and
this is what you will be in the eyes

00:17:11.790 --> 00:17:13.190
of the Colombian public."

00:17:13.190 --> 00:17:16.360
So this is the power they have,
which is sometimes unfair.

00:17:16.360 --> 00:17:19.340
But you know, who cares.

00:17:19.340 --> 00:17:21.980
[Laughter]

00:17:21.980 --> 00:17:24.380
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Your work has
been described as a reaction

00:17:24.380 --> 00:17:28.770
to magic realism, of which
we've read so much coming

00:17:28.770 --> 00:17:30.500
from great Latin American authors.

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:35.050
How you feel about that?

00:17:35.050 --> 00:17:37.700
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: I think
that has always, even with the best

00:17:37.700 --> 00:17:40.180
of intentions, has always
been oversimplified.

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:48.520
What I feel is gratitude
towards Garcia Marquez.

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:54.320 position:56%
One of the great advantages --
Garcia Marquez doesn't need any kind

00:17:54.320 --> 00:17:58.840
of presentation, but he is of
course credited with having

00:17:58.840 --> 00:18:05.960
in a way invented this new lens
-- it was new in the 60's --

00:18:05.960 --> 00:18:09.170
to examine Latin American
reality which is magical realism,

00:18:09.170 --> 00:18:14.800
which was taken up by
writers all over the world.

00:18:14.800 --> 00:18:25.580
So nobody ever asks Salman Rushdie
or Mo Yan in China or Ben Okri

00:18:25.580 --> 00:18:32.380 position:56%
in Nigeria or [Inaudible] in the
French Caribbean, how did they write

00:18:32.380 --> 00:18:34.530
under the influence
of Garcia Marquez?

00:18:34.530 --> 00:18:38.780
But I get that question
all the time.

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:40.080
[Laughter]

00:18:40.080 --> 00:18:41.850
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Do you notice
how artfully I actually left

00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:43.150
out his name?

00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:44.450
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
Yes, very good.

00:18:44.450 --> 00:18:45.750
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I was trying

00:18:45.750 --> 00:18:47.050
to avoid asking you
for the umpteenth time.

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:49.350
Sorry.

00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:57.810
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
So the thing with this is

00:18:57.810 --> 00:19:07.070
that this question that you
have so artfully not asked,

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:11.790
it presupposes there is a sort
of territorial relationship

00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:19.810
and influence, that
influence is territorial.

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:25.850
It's justifiable, but it's
almost never true in literature.

00:19:25.850 --> 00:19:31.240
The fact that I'm Colombian in
no way means that the influence

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:35.750
of the great Colombian writer
immediately falls on my shoulders,

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:40.630
like it's not influenced by
influenza, like you're going

00:19:40.630 --> 00:19:42.300
through the streets
and somebody sneezes,

00:19:42.300 --> 00:19:48.240
and you get magical
realism all of a sudden.

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:52.440 position:56%
[Laughter] Writers, and Garcia
Marquez is the best example of this,

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:54.590
when he started writing novels,

00:19:54.590 --> 00:19:57.980
there was no Columbia
novelistic traditions to speak of.

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:03.090 position:56%
We had a couple of great novels, but
there was not a tradition as such.

00:20:03.090 --> 00:20:08.830
And so, he decided his master
would be Faulkner because he wrote

00:20:08.830 --> 00:20:12.260
about a world very similar to
the world of Garcia Marquez.

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:17.590
And then he got tired of Faulkner,
and, in a way, hired Hemingway.

00:20:17.590 --> 00:20:22.850
Come, teach me how
to write short novels

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:25.640
with spare dialogues
and economic prose.

00:20:25.640 --> 00:20:28.840
And so, Hemingway did
the trick for one book.

00:20:28.840 --> 00:20:34.050
And so, this mixture of
influences, Faulkner, Hemingway,

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:40.680
Kafka -- a little bit of Kafka.

00:20:40.680 --> 00:20:45.370
For his second novel,
"An Evil Hour,"

00:20:45.370 --> 00:20:47.950
he copied Albert Camus, in a way.

00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:52.040
And that cocktail -- none of
these writers were Colombian --

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:56.400
and that cocktail allowed
him to discover his voice,

00:20:56.400 --> 00:21:00.950
the voice in which he wrote
"One Hundred Years of Solitude."

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:04.010
That is more or less the
way it worked for me.

00:21:04.010 --> 00:21:06.880
I grew up with Garcia
Marquez as a reader.

00:21:06.880 --> 00:21:11.010
I have always admired Garcia
Marquez as a novelist.

00:21:11.010 --> 00:21:12.310
I think he is one of the two

00:21:12.310 --> 00:21:17.890
or three great stylists
in the Spanish language.

00:21:17.890 --> 00:21:23.100
But these images, these
characters that I had

00:21:23.100 --> 00:21:25.930
in my head needed a different shape

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:29.480
than magical realism
was able to provide.

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:35.150 position:56%
I found that in other Latin American
writers, such as Mario [Inaudible]

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:39.650 position:56%
or Juan Carlos Zanetti from Uruguay.

00:21:39.650 --> 00:21:42.920
I found that in American writers

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:47.690
like Philip Roth, in
European writers.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:51.170
You don't want to know
the list of them.

00:21:51.170 --> 00:21:57.390
But this is how influence,
in a way, happens.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:22:02.240
You have this image in your
head, and you choose the writers

00:22:02.240 --> 00:22:06.980
who have the tools you need to
make that become literature.

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:11.530
In my case, it wasn't
Garcia Marquez.

00:22:11.530 --> 00:22:15.750
There is one advantage I have
over Garcia Marquez is the fact

00:22:15.750 --> 00:22:19.760
that I write in a world in which
Garcia Marquez already exists.

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:21.300
He didn't.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:25.530
He didn't write in a world in which
Garcia Marquez had already written

00:22:25.530 --> 00:22:26.830
his wonderful novels.

00:22:26.830 --> 00:22:33.040
So my tradition is better for
that fact and I'm lucky here.

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:34.340
So this is what happens.

00:22:34.340 --> 00:22:35.640
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Yeah.

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:36.940
We want to invite your questions.

00:22:36.940 --> 00:22:38.470
There are a couple of
microphones up here.

00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:42.210
