00:22:54.280 --> 00:22:58.580
As people advance on the mic,
let me work in one more question.

00:22:58.580 --> 00:23:02.030
You spent years living in
Europe, Paris, Barcelona.

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:05.640
Easier or harder to
write about Columbia

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:08.400 position:56%
in Columbia than it was from Europe?

00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:09.700
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Both.

00:23:09.700 --> 00:23:18.250
It was definitely easier in
the sense that that cliché,

00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:22.500 position:56%
that unique perspective to talk
about your own country that you need

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:29.600
to get out of the woods in
order to have a better look

00:23:29.600 --> 00:23:32.900
at the whole thing,
that's really true.

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:37.610
But on the other hand, I
started writing novels in a world

00:23:37.610 --> 00:23:42.320
in which the Internet was not
as all- pervading as it is now.

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:49.130
So for my first real novel,
which is called "the Informers,"

00:23:49.130 --> 00:23:52.490
I didn't have a strong relationship
with the Internet at that time.

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:59.890
I wrote that novel in 2002,
so I remember perfectly having

00:23:59.890 --> 00:24:04.760
to call my father and ask him
to go to such-and-such corner.

00:24:04.760 --> 00:24:07.290
Tell me what you see there.

00:24:07.290 --> 00:24:10.550
Are you able to see the door

00:24:10.550 --> 00:24:15.250
where Jorge Eliécer Gaitán left the
building before he was murdered?

00:24:15.250 --> 00:24:21.560
And so I had these informers that
allowed me to write my books.

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:22.860
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Yeah.

00:24:22.860 --> 00:24:24.900
And now of course,
that's on Google maps.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.200
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Exactly.

00:24:26.200 --> 00:24:27.800
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Has anyone
advanced on the microphones?

00:24:27.800 --> 00:24:30.990
