00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:27.010
of the extreme right
wing [inaudible].

00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:35.530
Different stories are told by
an inhabitant of the cities.

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:40.160
And a different story if
it's being told by a peasant.

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:42.070
So what do we do with this?

00:35:42.070 --> 00:35:45.740
I think this where
literature can step in and try

00:35:45.740 --> 00:35:52.810
to reconcile all the different
versions of our last 50 years,

00:35:52.810 --> 00:35:57.480
or try to communicate the idea

00:35:57.480 --> 00:36:01.230 position:56%
that having all these very different
versions is not a handicap.

00:36:01.230 --> 00:36:02.590
It's good.

00:36:02.590 --> 00:36:06.710
This is what democracy is
about, telling different stories

00:36:06.710 --> 00:36:13.810 position:56%
about the same thing and having them
all be part of the Colombian story.

00:36:13.810 --> 00:36:17.340
So this is, I think,
what we should try to do.

00:36:17.340 --> 00:36:20.240
This is the reason I
write novels in a way,

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:26.850 position:56%
to try to validate a certain version
of history of our common past,

00:36:26.850 --> 00:36:28.180
keeping in mind that it's different

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:32.770
from other versions,
and that's good.

00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:34.370
So, yeah.

00:36:34.370 --> 00:36:35.680
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Yes, ma'am?

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:38.400
&gt;&gt; Questioner: That sort
of leads into my question.

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:39.850
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Good.

00:36:39.850 --> 00:36:44.480
&gt;&gt; Questioner: Do you think
novelists are esteemed

00:36:44.480 --> 00:36:50.650
or valued differently in Columbia
and they are in this country?

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:51.950
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez: Yes.

00:36:51.950 --> 00:36:55.780
Yes, I didn't really do.

00:36:55.780 --> 00:37:00.990
I think for reasons that
would be too long to explain

00:37:00.990 --> 00:37:09.020 position:56%
and that I don't really understand
completely, the position of a writer

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:11.280
in the American tradition is
different from the position

00:37:11.280 --> 00:37:14.080
of a writer in the Latin
American tradition.

00:37:15.910 --> 00:37:20.030
Maybe because, as Latin Americans,

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:25.570
we come from the French
ideal of the intellectual.

00:37:25.570 --> 00:37:32.090 position:56%
So novelists are expected to
participate in the political debate,

00:37:32.090 --> 00:37:39.840
to participate in the social
debates of their time.

00:37:39.840 --> 00:37:45.540
In that changes the
situation of writers.

00:37:45.540 --> 00:37:52.610
I don't think an American novelist
would be expected immediately

00:37:52.610 --> 00:37:57.260
to have all the answers ready
as to the political situation

00:37:57.260 --> 00:38:00.830
of their country at
any public event.

00:38:00.830 --> 00:38:06.660
As Latin Americans, we know
we are, and it's not easy.

00:38:06.660 --> 00:38:12.570
And we always have to keep in mind
that ours is the tradition also

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:19.250
of such great writers that
shapes 20th century literature

00:38:19.250 --> 00:38:23.110
as Jorge Luis Borges, who is not

00:38:23.110 --> 00:38:27.220
in any recognizable
way a political writer.

00:38:27.220 --> 00:38:29.800
He was not a political writer
in the sense that Garcia Marquez

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:31.420
or Mario Vargas Llosa were.

00:38:31.420 --> 00:38:33.900
So we have both worlds
in Latin America,

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:42.880
but there is this expectation that
novelists should fulfill that idea.

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:45.680
It's not always fair.

00:38:45.680 --> 00:38:56.050 position:56%
Garcia Marquez himself said the
writer's only task is to write well.

00:38:56.050 --> 00:38:57.660
Some days I agree with him.

00:38:57.660 --> 00:38:59.980
Some days I don't.

00:38:59.980 --> 00:39:05.850
I think that's the
main difference, yes.

00:39:05.850 --> 00:39:10.460
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: Juan Gabriel
Vasquez, it's been a great honor

00:39:10.460 --> 00:39:12.120
for me to be his interlocutor here.

00:39:12.120 --> 00:39:13.420
Thank you very much.

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:17.000
The book we spoke about
is "Reputations."

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:20.000
You'll be available to sign
the odd copy if someone asks?

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:23.580
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
Yes, as many as you want.

00:39:23.580 --> 00:39:25.470
&gt;&gt; Scott Simon: I believe, as
we say in the United States,

00:39:25.470 --> 00:39:26.990
you'll sign until the
cows come home.

00:39:26.990 --> 00:39:28.820
Thank you very much for joining us.

00:39:28.820 --> 00:39:30.230
It's been great.

00:39:30.230 --> 00:39:32.030
&gt;&gt; Juan Gabriel Vasquez:
Yes, thank you.

